Capuchins Home Ranges and Core Areas

Autocorrelated Kernel Density Estimators

Index HMM Daily Travels

To estimate capuchins monthly home ranges (95% isopleth) and core areas (50% isopleth) we fitted OrnsteinUhlenbeck (OU) and OrnsteinUhlenbeck Foraging (OUF) movement models. Datasets that better fit Independent Identically Distributed (IID), Brownian Motion (BM) were excluded because they did not accomplish the criteria described below. We selected the best-fitting model using the lowest Akaike Information Criterion (AIC; Akaike, 1974; Calabrese et al., 2016). After identifying the optimal movement model, we calculated Autocorrelated Kernel Density Estimates (AKDE), which account for positional and temporal autocorrelation. We specifically applied weighted AKDE to correct for uneven sampling, assigning higher weights to under-sampled intervals and lower weights to over-sampled intervals. This approach effectively handles datasets with missing or irregular data (Fleming et al., 2019; Noonan et al., 2019).

3 Calculating AKDEs

The data in the following table was obtained after running a function I created: sim_akde.R.
For more details on the function, check the link.

This function generates a summary table of the 95% and 50% AKDEs for each independent dataset; in this case, the monthly locations for each group (AKDEs from different months).

Datasets with small effective size (<30) were discarded. We discarted AKDEs with no residence behavior based on variograms plotted using ctmm package.
I do not think it is appropriate to compare areas estimated under an autocorrelated movement model (which adjusts the bandwidth based on point correlation; OU, OUF) and non-autocorrelated models.

Additionally, sim_akde.R generates a shapefile for each AKDE, which we will use later to estimate proportions of each habitat type within plantations landscapes (pine stands and native forest fragments).

3.0.1 Rarerifying data

rarefy_gps <- function(data) {
  data <- data %>%
    mutate(
      date = as.Date(timestamp),
      rounded_time = timestamp - (as.numeric(timestamp) %% (90 * 60))
    ) %>%
    group_by(individual.local.identifier, date) %>%
    filter(abs(difftime(timestamp, rounded_time, units = "mins")) <= 15) %>%
    slice_min(order_by = abs(difftime(timestamp, rounded_time, units = "mins")), n = 8, with_ties = FALSE) %>%
    ungroup() %>%
    arrange(individual.local.identifier, timestamp)
  
  return(data)
}

hr_stand <- rarefy_gps(hr)
sim_akde <- function(data, output_dir = "ctmm_fits/monthly/") {
  
  shapes_dir <- file.path(output_dir, "shapes")
  
  if(!dir.exists(output_dir)) dir.create(output_dir, recursive = TRUE)
  if(!dir.exists(shapes_dir)) dir.create(shapes_dir, recursive = TRUE)
  
  results <- data.frame(
    individual.local.identifier = character(),
    best_fit = character(),
    akde_95_area = numeric(),
    akde_50_area = numeric(),
    n_locs = integer(),
    stringsAsFactors = FALSE
  )
  
  unique_ids <- unique(data$individual.local.identifier)
  
  for (id in unique_ids) {
    
    telemetry_data <- data %>% filter(individual.local.identifier == id)
    
    telemetry_object <- as.telemetry(telemetry_data, timezone = "America/Argentina/Buenos_Aires")
    
    guess <- ctmm.guess(telemetry_object, CTMM = ctmm(error = 20), interactive = FALSE)
    
    fits <- ctmm.select(telemetry_object, CTMM = guess, verbose = TRUE)
    
    saveRDS(fits, file = file.path(output_dir, paste0(id, "_fits.RDS")))
    
    akde_result <- akde(data = telemetry_object, CTMM = fits[[1]], weights = TRUE)
    
    n_eff <- summary(akde_result)$DOF["n_eff"]
    if (n_eff > 30) {
      akde_sf_95 <- as.sf(akde_result, level.UD = 0.95, level = 0.95) %>% st_transform(32721)
      akde_sf_50 <- as.sf(akde_result, level.UD = 0.5, level = 0.5) %>% st_transform(32721)
      
      akde_95 <- akde_sf_95 %>% filter(name == paste0(id, " 95% est"))
      akde_50 <- akde_sf_50 %>% filter(name == paste0(id, " 50% est"))
      
      st_write(akde_95, file.path(shapes_dir, paste0(id, "_akde_95.shp")), delete_layer = TRUE)
      st_write(akde_50, file.path(shapes_dir, paste0(id, "_akde_50.shp")), delete_layer = TRUE)
      
      best_fit_name <- if (is.list(fits) && length(fits) > 0) {
        summary(fits[[1]])$name
      } else {
        NA
      }
      
      results <- rbind(results, data.frame(
        individual.local.identifier = id,
        best_fit = best_fit_name,
        akde_95_area = as.numeric(st_area(akde_95)),
        akde_50_area = as.numeric(st_area(akde_50)),
        n_locs = nrow(telemetry_data)
      ))
    }
  }
  
  return(results)
}

Apply the function

4.1 Landscape ShapeFiles

The sim_akde function saved multiple Shapefiles corresponding to each home range (AKDE95) and core area (AKDE50). These shapefiles are not only useful for creating maps but also for calculating important metrics, such as the proportion of Native Forest without management (BNSM; abreviation in spanish) or pine plantations.

There are many shapefiles (2 per home range, totaling 190).

I read all the Shapefiles from the monthly folder (where sim_akde saved them) based on their file extension. I kept the full.names option because sim_akde saved the files preserving the group_year_month format, which is useful to later split them into a dataframe and match them with the summary table of the AKDEs.

Applying st_read to all elements in the list was problematic, since it generated too many automatic messages in the HTML output, including CRS information for each of the 190 shapefiles, bounding boxes, etc. To avoid this, I did the following:

files_shp <-
  list.files(path = "/shapes",
             pattern = "\\.shp$",
             full.names = TRUE)

lista_shapefiles <- lapply(files_shp, st_read)

Need to add an aditional shape of other timber company

BNSM_shapefile <- st_read("files/BNSM.shp")
## Reading layer `bnsm' from data source 
##   `C:\Users\Usuario\Desktop\Doctorado\Cap2\paper\codes\paper_codes\files\bnsm.shp' 
##   using driver `ESRI Shapefile'
## Simple feature collection with 217 features and 21 fields
## Geometry type: POLYGON

## Geodetic CRS:  WGS 84

To store all the results generated during the process, I first create an empty list.

The first line extracts the CRS used by Arauco for their shapefile (in case they used an uncommon one).

lapply iterates over all the shapefiles (190 in total) and reprojects the coordinates according to the CRS of the BNSM layer using st_transform(). This ensures that all shapefiles in lista_shapefiles are in the same CRS.

  • The for loop iterates through each shapefile in lista_shapefiles_transformada.
  • In each iteration, it extracts the filename using basename(), which returns only the file name without the full path (useful for identifying which file is being processed).
  • Then, it calculates the geometric intersection between the transformed shapefile and BNSM_shapefile using st_intersection(). This returns the geometry corresponding to the overlapping area between the two shapefiles.
  • Next, it calculates the total area of the transformed shapefile using st_area(), which returns the areas of all geometries in the shapefile, and then sums these areas using sum().
  • It also calculates the area of the intersection (i.e., the overlapping region between the current shapefile and BNSM_shapefile).
  • Finally, it computes the proportion by dividing the intersection area by the total area and stores all the results in a data frame.
resultados <- list()
crs_bsnm <- st_crs(BNSM_shapefile)

lista_shapefiles_transformada <- lapply(lista_shapefiles, function(shapefile) {
  st_transform(shapefile, crs_bsnm)
})


for (i in seq_along(lista_shapefiles_transformada)) {

  nombre_shape <- basename(archivos_shp[i])
  

  interseccion <- st_intersection(lista_shapefiles_transformada[[i]], BNSM_shapefile)
  

  area_shape <- sum(st_area(lista_shapefiles_transformada[[i]]))
  area_interseccion <- sum(st_area(interseccion))
  
 
  proporcion <- as.numeric(area_interseccion / area_shape)
  
  
  resultados[[i]] <- data.frame(
    Shape = nombre_shape,
    Proporcion_BNSM = proporcion)
}

df_resultados <- do.call(rbind, resultados)


df_resultados <- df_resultados %>%
  separate(Shape, 
           into = c('Group', 'year', 'mes', 'akde', 'isopleth'), 
           sep = '_')

df_resultados_wide <- df_resultados %>%
  mutate(isopleth = gsub("\\.shp", "", isopleth)) %>%  
  pivot_wider(names_from = isopleth, 
              values_from = Proporcion_BNSM, 
              names_prefix = "prop_bnsm_")

hr_month <- hr_month %>%
  left_join(df_resultados_wide, by = c("grupo", "year", "mes"))

4.2 Bark-stripping

Over a 2-year sampling period (20212023), we monthly measured intensity of bark-stripping on 2000 pine trees distributed across 40 transects, randomly placed within the home ranges of four black capuchin groups. As a proxy of pine phloem consumption, we measured the total bark-stripped area per pine, calculated as the lateral surface area of a truncated cylinder (Kershaw et al.2016), using the recorded start and end heights of the debarked area and a taper parameter (k), derived from preliminary measurements on 24 pines to adjust for tree growth patterns specific to the study area. \[ A = \pi \times \frac{D_i}{2} \left( \frac{1}{1+ e^{k (h_{\text{lower}}- h_i ) }} + \frac{1}{1+ e^{k (h_{\text{upper}}- h_i ) }} \right) \times \sqrt{ h^2 + \frac{D_i}{2} \left( \frac{1}{1+ e^{k (h_{\text{lower}}- h_i ) }} + \frac{1}{1+ e^{k (h_{\text{upper}}- h_i ) }} \right) } \] Where \(A\) is the total lateral surface area debarked,
\(D_i\) is the diameter at breast height (DBH; 1.3 m above the ground),
\(k\) is the taper parameter that adjusts the rate of diameter reduction with height,
\(h_{\text{lower}}\) and \(h_{\text{upper}}\) are the heights where the bark-stripping starts and ends, respectively,
and \(h_i\) is the fixed reference height (1.3 m).

We will add the bark-stripping monitoring to the AKDE dataset

4.3 Fruit Ripening

For capuchins living in plantations and Iguaz National Park (INP), we included fruit ripening season as a covariate, as it has been reported to influence space use patterns (Di Bitetti 2001a) . Since our data spans over a decade, we established a broad categorization based on two independent data sources. To define this classification, we used phenology data from Di Bitetti (2001a), collected in INP, and 20212023 phenological surveys conducted in San Jorge Reserve, a private protected area located between the plantation study site and INP (-25.766703, -54.309295). Phenological surveys conducted between June 2021 and October 2023 consisted of transect-based monitoring, in which we bimonthly recorded the phenological state of 416 individuals from 52 tree and liana species known to be consumed by capuchins (Di Bitetti 2001b). During each survey, we classified fruit ripening into four levels: 0 (no ripe fruits), 1 (010% ripening relative to its maximum), 2 (1030%), and 3 (>30%), following Agostini et al.(2010). Each species was further categorized according to its importance in the capuchin diet (Di Bitetti 2001b) as Low, Intermediate, or High. Based on this information (Figure B.1), we classified MayAugust as low fruit ripening months and SeptemberApril as high fruit ripening months.

smoothed_feno <- readRDS('files/smoothed_feno.rds')

Figure B.1.: Seasonal trends in fruit ripening levels based on phenological surveys conducted between June 2021 and October 2023 in northeastern Argentina. The solid lines represent the mean fruit ripening index for tree and liana species consumed by Black Capuchins Monkeys (Sapajus nigritus), categorized by their dietary importance: High (purple), Intermediate (teal), and Low (green). The shaded areas indicate the standard deviation for each category. Fruit ripening was classified into four levels: 0 (no ripe fruits), 1 (010% ripening), 2 (1030%), and 3 (>30%). Based on these patterns, we classified MayAugust as low fruit ripening months and SeptemberApril as high fruit ripening months.

set.seed(123)
folds <- createFolds(hr_month2$log_akde_95_area, k = 10, list = TRUE)
errors <- numeric(length(folds))

for (i in seq_along(folds)) {
  train_data <- hr_month2[-folds[[i]], ]  
  test_data <- hr_month2[folds[[i]], ]   
  
  model <- lmer(log_akde_95_area ~ area + productividad + n_ind + (1 | grupo), 
                data = train_data)
  
  predictions <- predict(model, newdata = test_data, allow.new.levels = TRUE)
  
  errors[i] <- mean((predictions - test_data$log_akde_95_area)^2)
}

mean_cv_error <- mean(errors)
rmse_log <- sqrt(mean_cv_error)  
typical_error_percentage <- (exp(rmse_log) - 1) * 100  


model_performance <- data.frame(
  Metric = c("Marginal R (Rm)", "Conditional R (Rc)", "RMSE (log scale)", "Typical Error (%)"),
  Value = c(r2m, r2c, rmse_log, typical_error_percentage)
)


model_performance %>%
  flextable() %>%
  theme_tron_legacy() %>%  
  colformat_num(j = "Value", digits = 3) %>%
  bold(part = "header") %>%
  autofit() %>%
  set_caption("Model Performance Summary: R and RMSE")

The selected model explained a substantial proportion of the variance in home range size, with fixed effects accounting for 78.85% (Rm = 0.789) of the variance and the total model explaining 90.51% (Rc = 0.905).

Cross-validation supported the robustness of the model, yielding an average root mean square error (RMSE) of 0.1966 in the log-transformed scale. When back-transformed to the original scale, this corresponds to an approximate 2.17 10% typical error.
